  "title": "",
  "body": "  A travel agency offers a vacation package where you select one destination and one resort. You can choose from three destinations: Hawaii, Florida, and Alaska. In Hawaii, you can stay at either of 2 resorts. In Florida, you can choose from 3 different resorts. In Alaska, only 1 resort is available. How many different vacation packages are possible in total?     This process can be broken up into two steps:  pick a destination (there are three of them);  pick a resort (the number depends on the destination chosen in step 1).     Vacations.   A three with one branch from the starting point for each destination, Hawaii, Florida, and Alaska. Hawaii has two branches for its two resorts, Florida has three branches for its three resorts, and Alaska has one branch.      Since the number of options in Step 2 depends on the choice made in Step 1, we cannot apply the multiplication rule directly. Instead, we use a tree diagram, as shown above. This diagram illustrates how the number of available choices varies based on the selected destination. Notice that there are six branches at the final level of the tree, indicating six distinct vacation package combinations. The tree diagram effectively captures the conditional nature of the choices and helps visualize all possible outcomes.   "
