  "url": "sec-statistics-overview.html#subsection_statistics_confidence_interval-5",
  "type": "Example",
  "number": "4.1.26",
  "title": "",
  "body": "  Let's say we asked a random sample of 100 students at Walla Walla University and found that they spent an average of $451.32 on books their first year, plus or minus $85.63. Write this as a confidence interval, assuming a 95% confidence level.    If the margin of error was calculated to be plus or minus $85.63, then with a confidence level of 95% we could say that the average amount spent by the population is somewhere between $365.69 and $536.95.  These values are found by computing and   We could also write this as a confidence interval : ($365.69, $536.95).  Now we have come full circle and seen how we can use data from a sample to estimate the parameter we were interested in for our population.   "
